<paragraph id="574036D4FFF84175CA81EE4CFE60275E" blockId="14.[151,1437,1680,2031]" box="[199,466,1824,1851]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF84175CA81EE4CFEFA275F" bold="true" box="[199,328,1824,1850]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Reference:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFF84175CB09EE4DFE60275E" author="Hemp, C." box="[335,466,1825,1851]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" refId="ref16956" refString="Hemp, C. (2021) A Field Guide to the Bushcrickets, Wetas and Raspy Crickets of Tanzania and Kenya. Senckenberg Gesellschaft fur Naturforschung, Frankfurt, 451 pp." type="book" year="2021">Hemp 2021</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF84175CA81EE28FA2427C2" blockId="14.[151,1437,1680,2031]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF84175CA81EE28FED0273B" bold="true" box="[199,354,1860,1886]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF84175CB9CEE29FDAF273A" box="[474,541,1861,1887]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFF84175C8ABEE29FCF2273A" box="[749,832,1861,1887]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and spectrum of the song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF84175CEC4EE29FB762705" box="[1154,1220,1861,1888]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1287,1311]" captionTargetBox="[171,1410,201,1247]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[151,1436,181,1263]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Power spectra of male calling songs in Hetrodini species" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392725/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFF84175CBE1EE05FDA227E6" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[423,528,1897,1923]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song consists of a series of echemes repeated at 0.6 Hz and with about 30 syllables each (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF84175CBE2EEE1FE4827C2" box="[420,506,1933,1959]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1216,1240]" captionTargetBox="[154,1428,204,1175]" captionTargetId="figure-23@12.[151,1436,181,1192]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Cosmoderus and Enyaliopsis (figures of E. iaculator based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Cosmoderus femoratus, B Enyaliopsis bloyeti. C Enyaliopsis carolinus, D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, song type A, E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 (near ephippiatus), song type B, F Enyaliopsis iaculator, G Enyaliopsis jennae, H Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa. Left column overview (5-s-section), right column detail (250-ms-section)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392733/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
; see 
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFF84175C868EEE1FD3027C2" box="[558,642,1933,1959]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,236,476,501]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="TABLE 2. Song characteristics of Hetrodini species (for song type see Fig. 5 and text)" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" tableUuid="0380665CFFF1417CCAD1E8B0FBBD2190">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The first echeme of a series is often slightly longer than the following.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF84175CA81EEDCFE22278A" blockId="14.[151,1437,1680,2031]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF84175CA81EEDCFE8F27AF" bold="true" box="[199,317,1968,1994]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Genitalia.</emphasis>
The central part of the genitalic sclerites (titillator) of our specimens (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF84175CE17EEDDFB1527AE" box="[1105,1191,1969,1995]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1200,1224]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,237,1177]" captionTargetId="figure-41@13.[151,1436,237,1179]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Titillator and genitalic sclerites in Hetrodini, Enyaliopsina. First row A Cosmoderus femoralis (CH8627), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti (Kazimzumbwi), C Enyaliopsis carolinus (Minziro), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus (Rau Forest); second row E Enyaliopsis spec. 1 near ephippiatus (Mwala), F Enyaliopsis jennae (Uluguru), G Enyaliopsis spec. 2 (Mpwapwa), H Enyaliopsis spec. 3 (East Chenene); third row I Gymnoproctus rammei (Puge Simbo), J Gymnoproctus spec. (East Chenene)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392735/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="465">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
) is similar to that figured by 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFF84175CAB5EEB9FE3F278A" author="Glenn, G. S. Jr." box="[243,397,2005,2031]" pageId="14" pageNumber="465" pagination="67 - 102" refId="ref16270" refString="Glenn, G. S. Jr. (1991) A systematic revision of Enyaliopsis Karsch 1887 (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae, Hetrodinae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 117, 67 - 102. http: // www. jstor. org / stable / 25078540" type="journal article" year="1991">Glenn (1991)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFF94174CA81E9FAFC45209D" blockId="15.[151,1437,150,249]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFF94174CA81E9FAFEC920D5" bold="true" box="[199,379,150,176]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Chromosomes:</emphasis>
2n = 29 (28 + X0), FN = 29; pairs 1–14 and X chromosome acrocentric (
<specimenCount id="41F9FD5DFFF94174CEF9E9FAFAA920D4" box="[1215,1307,150,177]" pageId="15" pageNumber="466" type="male">2 males</specimenCount>
); thick (occupied the region next to the centromere) C-bands in the paracentromeric region in the long/medium chromosomes and the X chromosome, thin C-block in the short-sized autosomes (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFF94174C9CDE9B2FC5D209D" box="[907,1007,222,248]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1628,1652]" captionTargetBox="[203,1395,181,1598]" captionTargetId="figure-23@18.[172,1415,181,1604]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Examples of chromosome number and heterochromatin C-banding of mitotic male (A–C, G–K) and mitotic female complements (D), as well as diplotene/diakinesis (C, E, I on the right), and metaphase I (F) for the following Hetrodini taxa: A Cosmoderus femoralis, 2n = 24 + X0 (CH8626), B Enyaliopsis bloyeti, 2n = 28 + X0 (HE114), C Enyaliopsis carolinus, 2n =24 + neo-XY (CH8625), D Enyaliopsis ephippiatus, 2n = 26 + XX (female CH7849), E Enyaliopsis jennae, 2n = 26 + neo- XY (HE87), F Enyaliopsis spec. 2 Mpwapwa, 2n = 26 + X0 (CH8353), G Gymnoproctus rammei, 2n = 26 + X0 (CH8763), H Gymnoproctus spec., 2n = 26 + X0 (CH7953), I Spalacomimus magnus, 2n = 16 + X0 (CH7945), J Spalacomimus verruciferus, 2n = 22 + neo-XY (CH7897), K Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, 2n = 22 + neo-XY (CH7899). Bi-armed chromosomes (meta/submeta/subacrocentric) are marked with numbers (A, C, D, F–I); in the neo-XY system, sex chromosomes form association in diplotene (C) and metaphase I (I); arrowheads indicate interstitial C-bands in 1 (A, E, J, K) and 2 (I) pairs; asterisks (*) marked distal C-bands in 3, 4, 5 (C), 3, 4 (D), 2-heteromorphic (G, H) pair; X = neo-X and Y = neo-Y sex chromosomes. Scale bar = 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392745" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392745/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="466">Fig. 12B</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
